          "body": "Verse 3 contains the chapter's only imperative addressed to a human agent: 'Encourage the exhausted, and strengthen the feeble.' The command interrupts the flow of future-tense promises and lands a present-tense obligation. Someone — the prophet himself, or any messenger of God's word — must speak courage into the exhausted before the transformation arrives. Verse 4 provides the content of that speech: 'Take courage, fear not. Behold, your God will come.' The theological structure is precise: the ground of the command is the announcement, not the experience. The encourager does not say 'look around you, see how things are improving'; they say 'look ahead, your God is coming.' This is what the New Testament calls hope — confidence in what is not yet seen, grounded in the character and word of the One who promised (Hebrews 11:1; Romans 8:24-25). The New Testament parallel is strikingly close: Hebrews 12:12 quotes Isaiah 35:3 directly ('strengthen the hands that are weak and the knees that are feeble') and applies it to the community of faith running toward the eschatological Zion (Hebrews 12:22)."
