    "intro": "Interpretation asks what the text means — moving from observation (what does it say?) to discerning the author's intent in his original context and its canonical fulfillment. Isaiah 35 operates on three registers simultaneously: historical (a word to eighth-century Judah facing Assyrian collapse), typological (the exodus pattern of wilderness-highway-Zion), and eschatological (the final reversal of all exile). The movements below trace the chapter's argument pericope by pericope, showing how each wave builds toward the chapter's destination at everlasting joy on Zion.",
