        "number": 1,
        "title": "Creation's joy — the barren earth bears the glory of God",
        "range": "35:1-2",
        "excerpt": "The wilderness and the desert will be glad, And the Arabah will rejoice and blossom; Like the crocus… They will see the glory of the Lord, The majesty of our God.",
        "body": "Isaiah opens the chapter with an apostrophe — a direct address to the wilderness and the Arabah as if they are sentient participants in the coming redemption. This is not poetic decoration. The Old Testament's covenantal worldview understands the created order as deeply responsive to the moral and spiritual condition of the covenant people and their God. Creation was cursed when Adam fell (Genesis 3:17-18); it was subjected to futility (Romans 8:20). Its restoration is therefore not an add-on to redemption but a constituent part of it. The wilderness rejoicing is the garden returning.\n\nThe geography chosen — wilderness and Arabah — is the most hostile possible terrain, selected precisely because the reversal there is most dramatic. The Arabah is not a garden that has gone to seed; it is a place that has never been a garden. That it will 'rejoice and blossom like a crocus' is not agricultural improvement — it is new creation. The crocus (*chavatstselet*) likely evokes the wildflowers of the Sharon plain (Song of Songs 2:1) — a delicate, colorful bloom transplanted into the harshest landscape.\n\nThe theological summit of this opening movement is the clause that closes it: 'They will see the glory of the LORD, the majesty of our God' (35:2). The transformation of nature is not the end; it is the sign pointing to the end. The Hebrew *kavod* (glory) is the visible, weighty, self-manifesting presence of God — what Moses asked to see (Exodus 33:18), what filled the tabernacle (Exodus 40:34), what departed the temple in Ezekiel's vision (Ezekiel 10-11) and will return in Ezekiel 43. Isaiah announces that the wilderness will bear what the temple lost. The creation becomes the theater of divine self-disclosure.\n\nCalvin notes on this passage that God's glory is most brilliantly displayed precisely where nothing of human strength or beauty remains — the desert that praises is the desert that cannot take credit for its own flowering. The application to the church under persecution is precise: God displays His glory through the most desolate circumstances, not despite them.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Midbar* (wilderness) and *aravah* (Arabah) appear together in Deuteronomy 1-2 as the specific terrain of the Sinai wandering — Isaiah is invoking the Exodus geography deliberately. *Kavod* is the glory-word of the tabernacle and temple traditions. *Sus* (glad) and *gil* (rejoice) are both physical, bodily words for celebration — the land does not merely change; it exults."
