        "title": "Courage grounded in the coming God — the command before the transformation",
        "range": "35:3-4",
        "excerpt": "Encourage the exhausted, and strengthen the feeble. Say to those with anxious heart, 'Take courage, fear not. Behold, your God will come with vengeance; The recompense of God will come, But He will save you.'",
        "body": "The chapter's pivot from landscape to community is sudden. Verses 1-2 address the land; verses 3-4 address a human messenger and, through that messenger, a community of exhausted people. The imperatives are stacked: 'encourage,' 'strengthen,' 'say.' This is the chapter's only moment of present-tense obligation. Isaiah is commissioning speech — prophetic speech that announces what is not yet visible.\n\nThe people addressed are described with clinical precision: exhausted hands (*rapheh yadayim*, limp/slack hands), feeble knees (*kashol berekh*, stumbling knees), and anxious hearts (*mahar lev*, literally 'hasty/hurrying heart' — the idiom for panic). These are the physiological signs of a community that has been waiting too long, pressed too hard, and has begun to surrender hope. Hebrews 12:12-13 quotes directly from this verse, applying it to the Christian community running toward the eschatological Zion — the weariness Isaiah names in Judah is the same weariness the New Testament community faces.\n\nThe content of the speech is theologically precise: 'Behold, your God will come with vengeance; the recompense of God will come, but He will save you.' Three clauses, two negative toward the enemy and one positive toward the weak. God's coming has a double face: it is terrible for the oppressor (vengeance, *naqam*; recompense, *gemul*) and saving for the exhausted (yasah). The same act of divine arrival is simultaneously wrath and grace, depending on whose side of the relationship you occupy. This is not contradictory — it is the logic of the exodus: what was drowning for Pharaoh was salvation for Israel. The crossing of the same sea accomplished both.\n\nThe ground of courage is not circumstances improving but the certain arrival of the coming God. Isaiah does not say 'be encouraged because the Assyrians are weakening' — the historical situation of chapters 36-37 will show exactly the opposite. He says 'be encouraged because your God will come.' This is biblical hope in its strictest definition: confidence whose object is not present evidence but the character and word of God.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hinneh* (behold, 35:4) is the Hebrew particle of immediacy and importance — it introduces something the hearer must attend to urgently. *Naqam* (vengeance) and *gemul* (recompense) are both covenantal justice terms — God repays the breaking of His covenant (cf. Deuteronomy 32:35, which Paul quotes in Romans 12:19). *Yasah* (save) is the root of Jesus's name (Yeshua) — the etymology is not coincidental in a messianic context."
