        "body": "The 'then' (*az*) of verse 5 binds the healings to the coming announced in verse 4. These are not the natural progress of medical history; they are the consequence of God's arrival. The adverb does theological work: it makes the miracles signs of the new age inaugurated by God's coming, not improvements within the present age. When Jesus heals the blind, deaf, lame, and mute in Matthew 11 and Luke 7, the implicit claim is that the 'then' of Isaiah 35:5 has arrived. John the Baptist's question — 'Are You the Expected One?' — receives the answer in Isaiah's own vocabulary: 'the blind receive sight and the lame walk' (Matthew 11:4-5). The miracles are exegesis of the prophecy.\n\nIsaiah lists four specific disabilities: blindness (*ivver*), deafness (*cheresh*), lameness (*pisseach*), and muteness (*illem*). All four are conditions that isolated their sufferers from full participation in Israel's covenant life — blind and lame were excluded from priestly service (Leviticus 21:18); the deaf could not hear the reading of Torah; the mute could not join public praise. The healings therefore restore not merely physical function but covenant participation. The restored ones are immediately fitted for Zion: they can see the glory (35:2), hear the Torah, walk the highway (35:8), and shout joy (35:10).\n\nThe imagery of water in verses 6-7 follows the healings immediately and interprets them materially. Waters breaking forth in the wilderness, streams in the Arabah, the scorched land becoming a pool — these are the physical infrastructure of the healed community's journey. Isaiah 43:19-20 repeats the same pattern: 'I will even make a roadway in the wilderness, rivers in the desert… to give drink to My chosen people.' The water is both literal (provisions for the journey) and theological (the Spirit poured out, Isaiah 44:3; Joel 2:28; John 7:37-39). Douglas Moo's principle applies here by analogy: the material and spiritual registers reinforce rather than replace each other; both are real.\n\nThe transformation of the jackals' haunt (35:7) is the precise reversal of Isaiah 34:13 — the same habitat of desolation becomes productive vegetation. This is the chapter's internal proof of divine power: God does not merely improve the existing landscape; He transforms the very places cursed in the previous chapter.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Dalag* (leap, 35:6) — to leap, spring, bound — is used in Song of Songs 2:8 of the lover bounding over mountains. The word is reserved for effortless, joyful, athletic movement. *Baqa* (break forth, of waters, 35:6) is the same word used of the Red Sea being split — the waters' appearance in the wilderness carries Exodus freight. *Sharav* (scorched land/mirage, 35:7) — the shimmering heat-haze of the desert that deceives travelers; its transformation into a real pool is the reversal of illusion into substance."
