        "title": "The Highway of Holiness — a road that defines its travelers",
        "range": "35:8-9",
        "excerpt": "A highway will be there, a roadway, And it will be called the Highway of Holiness. The unclean will not travel on it… But the redeemed will walk there.",
        "body": "The chapter's third movement introduces its most theologically charged image: a highway through the wilderness, named the 'Highway of Holiness' (*derekh ha-qodesh*). The road is the spatial expression of the redemption — it connects the wilderness of exile with Zion, the city of God's presence. Isaiah 40:3 will announce the same road from the other direction: 'Clear the way for the LORD in the wilderness; make smooth in the desert a highway for our God.' The two texts bracket the Book of Comfort: the road announced in chapter 35 is the road prepared in chapter 40. John the Baptist is identified with the latter passage (Matthew 3:3; John 1:23), confirming that both refer to the way prepared for the coming Messiah.\n\nThe road's name is its theological program. It is not called the 'Highway of Power' or the 'Highway of the Victorious' but the 'Highway of Holiness.' Holiness (*qodesh*) is the absolute moral and ontological separateness of God, the term that defines His innermost character in Isaiah (the seraphim's cry: 'Holy, holy, holy,' 6:3). A road named for God's holiness is a road whose character corresponds to its Maker. The exclusions follow naturally: the unclean (*tame*) and the fool (*evil*) cannot travel it — not because guards bar the gate but because the road and the traveler are incompatible. This is not arbitrary exclusion but ontological incompatibility.\n\nThe positive definition is equally careful: 'But it will be for him who walks that way, and fools will not wander on it' (35:8, NASB). The traveler on the Highway of Holiness does not drift onto it; he walks it with deliberate direction. And verse 9 adds: 'the redeemed will walk there.' Redemption (*gaal*, the kinsman-redeemer's act) is what qualifies a traveler for the road — not personal holiness generated from within, but the holiness that comes from being bought back by the Holy One. This is the chapter's strongest soteriological note: access to the Highway of Holiness is through the act of the Redeemer, not through the purity of the traveler.\n\nThe safety clause of verse 9 — no lion, no vicious beast on the road — draws the sharpest contrast with the exile experience. The wilderness and the Arabah were full of predators; exiles who traveled them did so at lethal risk. The Highway of Holiness is a protected corridor: the same God who defeats the enemy at the cosmic level (34:1-4) clears the individual road of every predator. The journey to Zion is not only possible — it is safe.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Maslul* (highway, 35:8) — a built, raised road, the ancient equivalent of a paved military road. *Derekh* (way, 35:8) is the broader word for path or way of life — its combination with *qodesh* makes the road a moral as well as physical category. *Tame* (unclean) is Levitical purity language applied to the pilgrimage road — the journey to Zion has the structure of a pilgrimage toward the holy presence. *Gaal* (redeemed, 35:9) — the kinsman-redeemer's act; used for Boaz redeeming Ruth (Ruth 4) and for God redeeming Israel from Egypt (Exodus 6:6)."
