        "excerpt": "And the ransomed of the Lord will return And come with joyful shouting to Zion, With everlasting joy upon their heads. They will find gladness and joy, And sorrow and sighing will flee away.",
        "body": "The chapter's final verse is its doxological endpoint — and its most eschatologically freighted line. It appears almost verbatim in Isaiah 51:11, where it functions as the climactic promise of the central consolation section. The duplication is Isaiah's literary refrain, his way of marking this verse as the chapter's thesis statement and the book's consolation motif. The ransomed (*padah*, bought by payment) of the LORD will return and come to Zion — the journey begun on the Highway of Holiness (35:8) has reached its destination.\n\nThe joy is described in three registers. First, it is audible: 'joyful shouting' (*rinnah*) — the term for the pilgrims' shout as they arrived at the temple (Psalm 100:1-2; 118:15). The ransomed do not arrive silently; they arrive singing. Second, it is visible: 'everlasting joy upon their heads' — joy is not merely felt but worn, a crown of joy placed on the pilgrim's head, the ancient gesture of festive celebration (cf. Psalm 23:5). Third, it is permanent: *olam*, everlasting, forever. This is not the temporary relief after a battle or the brief happiness of a festival — it is the permanent eschatological condition of the redeemed.\n\nThe chapter's final stroke is the expulsion of sorrow and sighing: 'sorrow and sighing will flee away.' The verb is *nus* — to flee, to run away in retreat. Sorrow does not gradually diminish; it flees, as if driven by a pursuing force. The image reverses the exile experience: Israel fled from Babylon; in the new age, grief flees from Israel. Revelation 21:4 is the New Testament completion: 'He will wipe away every tear from their eyes; and there will no longer be any mourning, or crying, or pain; the first things have passed away.' What Isaiah announces as future, Revelation announces as accomplished.\n\nEdwards, in his *Notes on Scripture*, connects this verse to the doctrine of glorification — the believer's final state is not merely the absence of suffering but the positive, unending, intensifying joy of the presence of God. The 'everlasting joy' of Isaiah 35:10 is not a mood but a participation in the *kavod* (glory) announced in verse 2 — the ransomed have arrived where the glory is, and they share in it. Spurgeon, preaching on Isaiah 35, observed that the verse describes joy not as an emotion the redeemed generate but as a reality that overtakes them: 'gladness and joy will overtake them' — the blessing comes as a pursuer, not a passive availability.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Padah* (ransomed, 35:10) — to ransom by payment; distinct from *gaal* (35:9, redemption through kinship). Together the two words cover the full semantic range of liberation. *Rinnah* (joyful shouting) is the technical term for the pilgrims' processional shout at the temple. *Olam* (everlasting) — the duration word; here it definitively marks the joy as eschatological, not merely historical. *Nus* (flee) — the flight of enemies; the word reverses exile: sorrow flees as the ransomed advance."
